  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework for collective relation integration in knowledge graphs that leverages structurally informative motifs in unmatched regions of the target knowledge graph to generate pseudo-parallel subgraph pairs. Traditional relation alignment methods depend heavily on overlapping entities or pre-aligned triples, which are often scarce or noisy in real-world scenarios. Our method addresses this limitation by identifying recurrent, semantically meaningful subgraph motifs (e.g., hub-and-spoke, chain, triangle) within structurally rich but unmatched regions of the target KG. Using a motif-aware graph encoder trained via structural mutual information maximization—inspired by Deep Graph Structural Infomax—we extract latent representations of these motifs and match them to plausible counterparts in the source KG based on topological similarity and relational consistency, even in the absence of shared nodes. These matched pairs form 'pseudo-parallel' subgraphs, which are then used as training signals in a self-supervised contrastive objective to align relation schemas collectively. The model jointly optimizes three objectives: (1) maximizing agreement between pseudo-parallel subgraph embeddings, (2) preserving local and global structural fidelity via motif-level Information Bottleneck constraints, and (3) enforcing collective coherence among integrated relations through a graph-based message-passing module that propagates alignment confidence across interdependent relations. This enables the system to transfer relational knowledge from well-annotated source KGs to sparse or structurally divergent target KGs without relying on explicit supervision. The significance of this work lies in its ability to unlock previously unusable portions of incomplete KGs for integration, thereby improving coverage, robustness, and scalability in cross-KG reasoning. Potential impact includes advancing applications in biomedical knowledge fusion, cross-lingual semantic integration, and automated schema matching in enterprise systems where labeled data is minimal.",
