  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework, \u2018Structure-Conditioned Semantic Generative Alignment\u2019 (SCoSGA), that advances collective relation integration in knowledge graphs by generating semantically coherent pseudo-parallel subgraphs from unmatched regions through a generative modeling of structure-conditioned relation distributions. While existing methods rely on structural similarity alone to match motifs across KGs, they often fail to ensure semantic coherence in the absence of overlapping entities. SCoSGA addresses this by introducing a Motif-Aware Variational Graph Autoencoder (MA-VGAE) that jointly learns latent representations of subgraph structures and their associated relation type distributions using a hierarchical graph encoder. The model is trained via a dual objective: (1) maximizing structural mutual information at both edge and neighborhood levels (extending DGSI principles), and (2) minimizing the KL-divergence between predicted and observed relation type distributions within each motif class (e.g., hubs, chains, triangles). This enables the model to infer \u2018what relations are likely to appear\u2019 given a specific structure in the target KG, even when no entities overlap. Using this learned conditional distribution, SCoSGA generates synthetic yet semantically plausible relation configurations in unmatched regions and retrieves structurally and semantically compatible counterparts from the source KG via cross-KG motif retrieval using Earth Mover\u2019s Distance in the joint structure-relation embedding space. These constitute high-fidelity pseudo-parallel subgraph pairs. A dual-channel GNN then encodes these pairs under a contrastive loss, while a Cross-Motif Attention Network (CMAN) enforces global consistency by modeling dependencies among aligned motifs across the KG\u2014for instance, ensuring that if multiple disease-centered hubs align, their \u2018causes\u2019 relations cohere semantically. The entire system operates in a self-supervised manner, requiring no labeled alignments. Significance lies in shifting from passive structural matching to active semantic generation guided by structural priors, enabling robust schema transfer in extremely sparse regimes. Impact spans biomedical KG fusion (e.g., aligning rare disease databases), cross-lingual ontology matching, and enterprise data integration where schemas evolve independently.",
